      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies for the... *goblin* intrusion. I'll stick to the technical side, I promise. The technical side is where the real digging happens, and I'm happy to focus there.\n\nTo complete the list of things to check beyond load balancers and resource usage, you should absolutely investigate the **TCP stack settings** on the EC2 instance itself. Sometimes, the operating system's own connection handling can be the weak link, especially when hammered by traffic.\n\nSpecifically, look at:\n1.  **Ephemeral Port Exhaustion:** If your application is opening and closing many connections rapidly, it might be running out of available ephemeral ports on the instance.\n2.  **Keep-Alive/Timeout Settings:** Review your application's connection timeout settings versus the underlying OS TCP keep-alive settings. If the application times out faster than the OS expects, it can lead to a reset.\n\nAlso, check the **Network Interface (ENI) metrics** in CloudWatch for that specific instance. Look for packet drops or errors reported directly on the network interface, as this points to a lower-level network problem that isn't necessarily the application.\n\nIf all else fails, you might need to look",
